","1224":"1224","2 May 1252":"2 mei 1252","1299":"1299","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","about 1236":"circa 1236","Folkington, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, England","Englefield, Berkshire, England":"Englefield, Berkshire, England","Eastbourne, East Sussex, England":"Eastbourne, East Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Isfield, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Isfield, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"5 September 1195–2 May 1252":"5 September 1195–2 May 1252","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1220–1276":"1220–1276","1226–1299":"1226–1299","1236–1265":"1236–1265","1174–1260":"1174–1260","1175–1243":"1175–1243","about 1194":"about 1194","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","bef 1252":"before 1252","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","5 September 1195":"5 September 1195","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","2 May 1252":"2 May 1252","1299":"1299","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","about 1236":"about 1236","Folkington, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, England","Englefield, Berkshire, England":"Englefield, Berkshire, England","Eastbourne, East Sussex, England":"Eastbourne, East Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Isfield, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Isfield, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Englefield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from either of two places called Englefield (in Berks and Surrey).  Compare  Inglefield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ingarfield","meanings":["English: locative name,  see  Englefield  ."]},{"name":"Inglefield","meanings":["English: locative name from Englefield (Surrey), recorded as  <i>Ingelfeld</i> in 1282, or Englefield (Berks)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Englefield was born on 5 September 1195, in Cornwall, England, her father, Sir William de Englefield, was 22 and her mother, Lady Emma de Dunstanville, Heiress of Shiplake, was 20. She had at least 1 daughter with Hugh de Folkington II. She died on 2 May 1252, in Eastbourne, East Sussex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"5 September 1195–2 May 1252":"5. september 1195–2. mai 1252","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1220–1276":"1220–1276","1226–1299":"1226–1299","1236–1265":"1236–1265","1174–1260":"1174–1260","1175–1243":"1175–1243","about 1194":"umbes 1194","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","bef 1252":"enne 1252","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","5 September 1195":"5. september 1195","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","2 May 1252":"2. mai 1252","1299":"1299","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","about 1236":"umbes 1236","Folkington, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, England","Englefield, Berkshire, England":"Englefield, Berkshire, England","Eastbourne, East Sussex, England":"Eastbourne, East Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Isfield, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Isfield, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"5 September 1195–2 May 1252":"5. syyskuuta 1195–2. toukokuuta 1252","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1220–1276":"1220–1276","1226–1299":"1226–1299","1236–1265":"1236–1265","1174–1260":"1174–1260","1175–1243":"1175–1243","about 1194":"noin 1194","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","bef 1252":"ennen vuotta 1252","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","5 September 1195":"5. syyskuuta 1195","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","2 May 1252":"2. toukokuuta 1252","1299":"1299","1243":"1243","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","about 1236":"noin 1236","Folkington, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, England","Englefield, Berkshire, England":"Englefield, Berkshire, England","Eastbourne, East Sussex, England":"Eastbourne, East Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Isfield, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Isfield, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"5 September 1195–2 May 1252":"5 septembre 1195–2 mai 1252","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1220–1276":"1220–1276","